---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="About AstroSEO.io" pathname="/about/">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="meta">About</p>
    <h1>Practical Astro publishing, with the evidence left in.</h1>
    <p>
      AstroSEO.io is an independent technical publication about building,
      auditing, and deploying content-focused Astro websites.
    </p>
  </section>

  <article class="policy-card prose">
    <h2>Purpose and audience</h2>
    <p>
      The site is for developers, independent publishers, and content teams who
      need concrete implementation details rather than generic SEO advice. The
      core topics are Astro architecture, technical SEO, static deployment,
      editorial workflows, and reusable publishing templates.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial principles</h2>
    <p>
      Articles are written around a specific problem and expected result. A
      retained tutorial includes commands, configuration, or a structured
      workflow; a saved evidence artifact; a verification method; and an honest
      limitation or recommendation. Overlapping search intents are consolidated
      instead of being expanded into multiple shallow pages.
    </p>

    <h2>Author and testing policy</h2>
    <p>
      AstroSEO.io is edited by Jun Yang. Tutorials are tested where practical
      against the repository and deployment described in the article. The site
      does not claim that one setup is universal, and it does not invent test
      results, credentials, professional qualifications, or performance data.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections and updates</h2>
    <p>
      Material changes to Astro, hosting platforms, or the demonstrated project
      can trigger a review. Reproducible corrections can be submitted through
      the public repository Issues page. Updated articles retain their stable
      URL whenever the original intent remains valid.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
